WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.300
[Music]

00:00:00.300 --> 00:00:12.390
Hi, I'm Norman Wildberger, and today we're going&nbsp;
to talk about laws of arithmetic. This is part&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:12.390 --> 00:00:18.870
of our foundations of mathematics series. So I&nbsp;
remind you up till now what we've done is first&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:18.870 --> 00:00:24.510
of all established what are the natural numbers. A&nbsp;
natural number is just a string of ones, and they&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:24.510 --> 00:00:33.270
form this very natural sequence like this. We have&nbsp;
two operations: addition and multiplication. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:33.270 --> 00:00:39.000
addition of two natural numbers is just what&nbsp;
you get when you combine them by juxtaposing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:47.940
them in the simplest possible way. Multiplication&nbsp;
is what you get when you take this many groups of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:47.940 --> 00:00:54.540
that one. So in other words, for every one in this&nbsp;
first number, you put a copy of the second number.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:54.540 --> 00:01:02.640
So 2 times 3 is 2 copies of 3: one there and one&nbsp;
there. And there are various laws. There are the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:02.640 --> 00:01:07.500
laws for addition: the commutative and associative&nbsp;
laws. There are laws for multiplication:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:07.500 --> 00:01:13.560
the commutative, associative, and identity laws,&nbsp;
and 2 distributive laws. And I left it to you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:13.560 --> 00:01:19.680
as a challenge last time to try to prove these&nbsp;
laws. Here we've already talked about these ones,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:19.680 --> 00:01:27.090
and this one is obvious. So today we want to talk&nbsp;
about why these laws are true, and we'll start&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:27.090 --> 00:01:34.410
with the commutative law of multiplication, which&nbsp;
says that n times m equals m times n. This is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:34.410 --> 00:01:41.190
in some sense, the most interesting of the laws.&nbsp;
Here's an example: 2 times 3. We have two groups&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:41.190 --> 00:01:48.030
of three: one there and one there. On the other&nbsp;
hand, if we think about three groups of two, or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:48.030 --> 00:01:56.520
three times two, we have three groups of two. Why&nbsp;
should it be that two groups of three is the same&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:56.520 --> 00:02:06.870
as three groups of two? This is already a subtle&nbsp;
point, and to explain why, let me change notation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:06.870 --> 00:02:13.590
just slightly, just temporarily. Instead of using&nbsp;
little sticks, I'll use circles for our basic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:13.590 --> 00:02:19.860
entities. So I've just rewritten here is two times&nbsp;
three: two groups of three. And now what I'm going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:19.860 --> 00:02:27.240
to do is I'm going to take those circles and I'm&nbsp;
going to rearrange them. Instead of putting them&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:27.240 --> 00:02:31.470
all in a row, I'm going to put one group of three&nbsp;
there and the other group of three on top of them.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:31.470 --> 00:02:39.900
Over here I've got three times two: that's three&nbsp;
groups of two, two, two, two. And again, I'm going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:39.900 --> 00:02:45.900
to do the same thing: I'm going to put the first&nbsp;
row there, then another row, and then another row.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:45.900 --> 00:02:51.960
So we have three groups of two stacked on top of&nbsp;
each other. Now why are these two the same? It's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:51.960 --> 00:02:57.300
because these two configurations visibly have&nbsp;
the same number of elements. We get one from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:57.300 --> 00:03:08.250
the other just by flipping. Our next law is the&nbsp;
associative law for multiplication: k times n done&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:08.250 --> 00:03:19.230
first times m is the same as k times what you get&nbsp;
when you take n times m. So let's illustrate with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:19.230 --> 00:03:26.040
an example. Suppose k is 2 and n is 3, and I'm not&nbsp;
going to suppose that m is anything in particular,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:26.040 --> 00:03:33.690
so we'll leave n as m as general. So we have 2&nbsp;
times 3 times m. The brackets tell us we need to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:33.690 --> 00:03:41.700
do 2 times 3 first: there's two groups of three,&nbsp;
so we have two groups of three times m. I remind&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:41.700 --> 00:03:46.830
you how to multiply: we simply have to replace&nbsp;
each one of the ones here with a copy of this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:46.830 --> 00:03:53.730
thing, so we have altogether n by m and then m.&nbsp;
Let me do it this way: when we do it the other&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:53.730 --> 00:04:01.140
way, it's 2 times 3 times m, so that's 2 times&nbsp;
what is three times m? It's what you get when you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:01.140 --> 00:04:09.270
replace each of the ones here with an m, so mmm.&nbsp;
We get 2 times m: that means we replace each one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:09.270 --> 00:04:14.970
of these with a copy of those, so we get mmm,&nbsp;
mmm, and we can see that we get the same thing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:14.970 --> 00:04:24.090
because in each case what we're really getting&nbsp;
is 2 times 3: there's 2 times 3 of them there,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:24.090 --> 00:04:32.540
and there's 2 times 3 of them there, and what m&nbsp;
is is immaterial. It will always be equal even&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:32.540 --> 00:04:42.140
if we don't use 2 and 3, use 3 and 4, or 4 and 5,&nbsp;
or anything else. Now the distributive laws, which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:42.140 --> 00:04:50.630
combine addition and multiplication. So the first&nbsp;
one is k times n plus m equals k times n plus k&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:50.630 --> 00:04:56.420
times m. Now I remind you this means we do this&nbsp;
multiplication and the multiplication before we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:56.420 --> 00:05:04.910
do the addition. Let's look at an example: suppose&nbsp;
k is 3, n is 2, and m is 1. Then k times n plus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:04.910 --> 00:05:14.600
m will be 3 times where this sum is 3, and I've&nbsp;
written the 3 in a way that keeps track of where&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:14.600 --> 00:05:21.440
the ones came from. So these two I'll mark in red&nbsp;
and this one in green, so if two red ones and one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:21.440 --> 00:05:30.560
green one, as opposed to three times that. So we&nbsp;
have one group, another group, another group. Now&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:30.560 --> 00:05:35.030
we are going to rearrange those: we're going to&nbsp;
take all the ones of the same color together,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:35.030 --> 00:05:40.490
so there are three groups of two red ones. We'll&nbsp;
put them all together there, and we'll bring all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:40.490 --> 00:05:47.330
the green ones: there's three ones over that side.&nbsp;
And we see that what we end up having is, in terms&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:47.330 --> 00:05:53.660
of the red ones, is three times two between&nbsp;
three groups of two red ones, and also we have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:53.660 --> 00:06:02.780
three groups of one green one. So 3 times 2 plus&nbsp;
1 is 3 times 2 plus 3 times 1, and this argument&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:02.780 --> 00:06:10.970
shows why it's true in general: we can always do&nbsp;
this kind of rearranging to convert this to this.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:13.400 --> 00:06:16.880
Alright, what about the other distributive law? We&nbsp;
could do it in the same way, but let me illustrate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:16.880 --> 00:06:21.890
another way of thinking about it using the laws&nbsp;
we've already established. If we have k plus n&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:21.890 --> 00:06:31.820
times m, we can use the commutative law to rewrite&nbsp;
that as m times k plus n. It's just commutativity,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:31.820 --> 00:06:39.940
and now we can use the distributive law we've&nbsp;
just proven to write that as m times k plus m&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:39.940 --> 00:06:47.590
times n. And each one of these two products can&nbsp;
be rewritten using the commutative law, so that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:47.590 --> 00:06:55.990
becomes k times m, and this one becomes n times&nbsp;
m, and that's what we require. So we have now&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:55.990 --> 00:07:05.350
proven all the laws of arithmetic so far. These&nbsp;
are the main laws of mathematics, and I think&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:05.350 --> 00:07:10.030
you can see that the arguments are simple enough&nbsp;
that with some patience, you could explain them to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:10.030 --> 00:07:16.150
a ten-year-old boy a hundred thousand years ago.&nbsp;
So is this the standard way that mathematicians&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:16.150 --> 00:07:23.800
think about the laws of arithmetic? No, it's not.&nbsp;
Most mathematicians believe that mathematics is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:23.800 --> 00:07:30.970
found on modern set theory, and they follow John&nbsp;
von Neumann's suggestion that we should define&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:30.970 --> 00:07:38.290
the natural numbers in terms of set theory. Zero,&nbsp;
which we haven't talked about but which represents&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:38.290 --> 00:07:47.830
nothing, is represented by the empty set. That's&nbsp;
reasonable. One is represented by a set which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:47.830 --> 00:07:53.350
contains one element, namely the zero that we've&nbsp;
just defined, so it's a set that contains within&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:53.350 --> 00:08:00.220
it the empty set. Also, we can't argue too much&nbsp;
with that. However, then the idea is that all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:00.220 --> 00:08:10.660
subsequent numbers are defined as sets of previous&nbsp;
numbers. So 2 is defined as {0, 1}, which is this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:10.660 --> 00:08:17.350
and 3 is defined as the set {0, 1, 2}, which is&nbsp;
this, and 4 is defined as the set {0, 1, 2, 3},&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:17.350 --> 00:08:25.780
and so on. And it gets more and more complicated&nbsp;
very quickly. So this is very complicated, it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:25.780 --> 00:08:30.880
overly complicated, it's certainly unintuitive,&nbsp;
it doesn't correspond to the way people think&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:30.880 --> 00:08:38.830
about numbers, and it's really divorced from&nbsp;
reality. It's an aspect of the way modern set&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:38.830 --> 00:08:44.800
theory has really distorted the entire discussion&nbsp;
about the foundations of mathematics. Modern set&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:44.800 --> 00:08:53.090
theory gave rise to the new math some 40-50 years&nbsp;
ago, which we all know now was sort of a disaster,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:53.090 --> 00:08:58.430
but less well-known is that it's also contributed&nbsp;
to very shaky and complicated foundations for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:58.430 --> 00:09:05.030
mathematics. One of our aims in this series will&nbsp;
be to look very critically at other deficiencies&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:05.030 --> 00:09:11.330
of modern set theory and to suggest, as we've&nbsp;
done here, replacements, some simpler ways of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:11.330 --> 00:09:18.020
thinking about the fundamental concepts. Next&nbsp;
time, subtraction and division: the other two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:18.020 --> 00:09:24.500
main operations in arithmetic. I hope you'll join&nbsp;
me. I'm Norman Wildberger, thanks for listening.

00:09:24.500 --> 00:09:31.740
Let me know if you need any further assistance!

